snippet.textDisplay: I have been asking for years why the vertical/horizontal or portrait/landscape issue can't be solved in software. If I forget and shoot something vertically, why can't the software automatically flip it for me regardless of how I held the phone when recording? I'm shooting vertically but internally, the phone can be shooting horizontally and then when I play it back it's in horizontal orientation. It could even be a toggle preference that users could turn on and off. I don't get why this hasn't been solved yet without ridiculous motorized TVs.

snippet.textDisplay: This car is a total mix of real car manufacturers. The front lights are from the Mazda RX-8. Nearly everything is copied from the Porsche Taycan, main style, door handles, panorama roof and even the black addons behind the front wheels, which is the loading port on the Porsche. The wheels are from the Porsche 718 Cayman. You'll find a large black area beneath the doors also on the BMW i8. The side style itself also has similaries to BMW. The back sloping roofline is from the Audi A7. The chrome front logo looks very similar to the one Citroën uses on their cars, but it's only one line. If some unknown chinese car company had shown this it would have been called a complete rip-off. But here it won't be said because of the well known slogan 'It's a Sony'. And if a combination of a VAIO Ericsson Playstation controlling is good for driving a car is another thing. If Sony had shown a car in the 80's, would they have reused keys from a Walkman, VU-Meters from tapedecks for the gauges, VFD-displays from a radio tuner for the speedometer and the steering wheel from a turntable? I won't say it looks bad, but this thing is as useless as printing Lamborghini on a backpack and paying the extra cash only for the name. Sony should stick to this what they can do: consumer electronics.

The wheels are from the Porsche 718 Cayman. You'll find a large black area beneath the doors also on the BMW i8. The side style itself also has similaries to BMW. The back sloping roofline is from the Audi A7. The chrome front logo looks very similar to the one Citroën uses on their cars, but it's only one line. If some unknown chinese car company had shown this it would have been called a complete rip-off. But here it won't be said because of the well known slogan 'It's a Sony'. And if a combination of a VAIO Ericsson Playstation controlling is good for driving a car is another thing. If Sony had shown a car in the 80's, would they have reused keys from a Walkman, VU-Meters from tapedecks for the gauges, VFD-displays from a radio tuner for the speedometer and the steering wheel from a turntable? I won't say it looks bad, but this thing is as useless as printing Lamborghini on a backpack and paying the extra cash only for the name.
